---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Footer from "../../components/Footer.astro";

// Define all blog posts
const posts = [
  {
    id: 1,
    slug: "a-day-at-the-studio",
    title: "A Day with me at FunGab Global Studio in Northumbria",
    category: "News & Updates",
    date: "January 11, 2026",
    author: "FunGab Team",
    image: "/blog/blog-1.png",
    content: `
      <p>
        Experience a behind-the-scenes look at our creative studio in Northumbria. From vocal recording to final mixing, 
        discover what goes into creating professional music that resonates with audiences worldwide.
      </p>
      
      <h3>The Creative Process</h3>
      <p>
        At FunGab Global, we believe that great music starts with great ideas. Our process begins with understanding your 
        vision, collaborating with you every step of the way to ensure your creative goals are met.
      </p>
      
      <h3>State-of-the-Art Equipment</h3>
      <p>
        Our studio is equipped with professional-grade recording equipment, mixing consoles, and acoustic treatment that 
        rivals any major facility. We invest in the best technology to ensure your music sounds exceptional.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Professional Team</h3>
      <p>
        Our experienced engineers and producers have worked on hundreds of projects across multiple genres. Whether you're 
        recording your first single or producing a full album, we bring expertise and creativity to every session.
      </p>
      
      <p>
        Ready to create something amazing? Contact us today to book your session at FunGab Global Studio.
      </p>
    `
  },
  {
    id: 2,
    slug: "find-your-unique-voice",
    title: "How to Find Your Own Unique Voice?",
    category: "Music Tips",
    date: "November 16, 2025",
    author: "Alex Johnson",
    image: "/blog/blog-2.png",
    content: `
      <p>
        Developing your signature sound is crucial in today's competitive music industry. Your unique voice is what sets you 
        apart from thousands of other artists. Here are proven techniques and strategies to discover your authentic voice.
      </p>
      
      <h3>1. Explore Different Genres</h3>
      <p>
        Don't limit yourself to one genre. Listen to a wide variety of music—from classical to electronic, jazz to hip-hop. 
        This exposure helps you understand different approaches to songwriting, production, and vocal expression.
      </p>
      
      <h3>2. Experiment with Production</h3>
      <p>
        Work with different producers and collaborators. Each collaboration brings new perspectives and techniques that can 
        influence your sound. Don't be afraid to try unconventional production choices.
      </p>
      
      <h3>3. Focus on Authenticity</h3>
      <p>
        Your unique voice comes from your personal experiences, emotions, and perspective. Write about what matters to you. 
        Be honest in your lyrics and performances. Audiences connect with authenticity.
      </p>
      
      <h3>4. Practice Vocal Techniques</h3>
      <p>
        Work with vocal coaches to develop your technical skills. Understanding breathing techniques, pitch control, and 
        vocal effects will give you more tools to express your unique sound.
      </p>
      
      <h3>5. Record and Review</h3>
      <p>
        Regularly record yourself and listen back critically. Identify what sounds good and what needs improvement. Over 
        time, you'll develop clarity about your sonic identity.
      </p>
    `
  },
  {
    id: 3,
    slug: "when-to-start-singing",
    title: "When Should I Start Singing Songs?",
    category: "Career Advice",
    date: "December 13, 2024",
    author: "Sarah Williams",
    image: "/blog/blog-3.png",
    content: `
      <p>
        Timing is everything in music. The question of when to start singing professionally is one many aspiring artists ask. 
        The answer? It depends on several factors. Let's explore when the right time might be for you.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Skill Development</h3>
      <p>
        Before launching as a professional singer, ensure you've developed solid vocal fundamentals. Work with a vocal coach, 
        practice regularly, and record demos to assess your readiness. Most professionals recommend at least 2-3 years of 
        focused development.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Original Material</h3>
      <p>
        Have you written original songs or identified songs that truly represent your style? Professional singers need a 
        distinctive catalog. Start with at least 5-10 well-developed original songs that showcase your voice and perspective.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Building Your Fanbase</h3>
      <p>
        In today's digital age, you don't need a record label to start. Use social media, streaming platforms, and live 
        performances to build an audience. Start performing when you have a group of loyal listeners who appreciate your work.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Market Conditions</h3>
      <p>
        Consider current market trends in your genre. Is there demand for your style of music? Research what's resonating 
        with listeners and position yourself accordingly. Sometimes waiting for the right moment means better opportunities.
      </p>
      
      <h3>The Right Mindset</h3>
      <p>
        Most importantly, ensure you're doing this for the right reasons. A sustainable career in music requires passion, 
        resilience, and commitment. If you're ready to work hard and face challenges, you're ready to start.
      </p>
    `
  },
  {
    id: 4,
    slug: "music-production-guide",
    title: "The Complete Guide to Modern Music Production",
    category: "Production",
    date: "January 5, 2026",
    author: "Marcus Chen",
    image: "/assets/services/music.png",
    content: `
      <p>
        Music production has evolved dramatically over the past decade. Whether you're recording your first track or refining 
        your craft, understanding modern production techniques is essential. This comprehensive guide covers everything from 
        recording to mastering.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Pre-Production</h3>
      <p>
        Before you hit record, plan your project. Define the overall vision, select instrumentation, and arrange your songs. 
        Spend time getting the arrangement right before moving to the recording phase.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Recording</h3>
      <p>
        Quality recording requires proper equipment and technique. Invest in good microphones and audio interfaces. Set up your 
        recording space with acoustic treatment to minimize unwanted reflections and noise.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Mixing</h3>
      <p>
        Mixing brings all elements together. Balance levels, EQ, compression, and effects to create a polished mix. Take 
        breaks to rest your ears and maintain perspective throughout the mixing process.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Mastering</h3>
      <p>
        Mastering is the final step that prepares your music for distribution. Use EQ, compression, and limiting to optimize 
        your mix for different playback systems and streaming platforms.
      </p>
    `
  },
  {
    id: 5,
    slug: "mixing-mistakes",
    title: "Top 10 Mixing Mistakes to Avoid",
    category: "Production",
    date: "December 28, 2025",
    author: "FunGab Team",
    image: "/assets/services/studio.png",
    content: `
      <p>
        Common mixing errors can ruin a great recording. Even experienced engineers make mistakes. Learn what professionals 
        avoid and elevate your mixing skills to the next level.
      </p>
      
      <h3>1. Mixing Too Loud</h3>
      <p>
        Loud mixing environments mask problems. Mix at moderate levels (around 85 dB) to make better decisions about EQ, 
        compression, and balance.
      </p>
      
      <h3>2. Not Taking Breaks</h3>
      <p>
        Ear fatigue leads to poor decisions. Take regular breaks to reset your hearing and maintain perspective on your mix.
      </p>
      
      <h3>3. Over-Compressing</h3>
      <p>
        Compression is powerful but easy to overuse. Use it to enhance, not to control every track. Leave room for dynamics.
      </p>
      
      <h3>4. Ignoring Phase Issues</h3>
      <p>
        Phase problems can cause subtle but noticeable frequency cancellation. Check phase alignment, especially with multiple 
        microphones on one instrument.
      </p>
      
      <h3>5. Poor Monitoring Environment</h3>
      <p>
        Your monitoring environment has the biggest impact on mixing quality. Invest in proper studio monitors and acoustic treatment.
      </p>
    `
  },
  {
    id: 6,
    slug: "studio-setup-guide",
    title: "Setting Up Your Home Recording Studio",
    category: "Equipment",
    date: "December 20, 2025",
    author: "Tech Expert",
    image: "/assets/services/recording.png",
    content: `
      <p>
        Building a professional home studio on any budget is possible with the right knowledge. We guide you through essential 
        equipment, room treatment, and optimization techniques.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Essential Equipment</h3>
      <p>
        Start with the basics: a quality audio interface, microphone, headphones, and monitor speakers. These four items will 
        enable professional-quality recordings.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Room Treatment</h3>
      <p>
        Acoustic treatment controls reflections and standing waves. Use absorption panels on walls and diffusers in corners. 
        Proper treatment dramatically improves recording quality.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Cable Management</h3>
      <p>
        Keep cables organized and away from audio cables to minimize interference. Use high-quality cables and proper shielding 
        to reduce electrical noise.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Monitoring Setup</h3>
      <p>
        Position monitors at ear level in a triangle formation with your listening position. This provides accurate stereo 
        imaging and frequency response representation.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Budget-Friendly Tips</h3>
      <p>
        Start small and upgrade gradually. Use thick blankets for acoustic treatment. Build relationships with other musicians 
        to share equipment and resources.
      </p>
    `
  }
];

// Get the post based on the slug
const { slug } = Astro.params;
const post = posts.find(p => p.slug === slug);

// Generate static paths for pre-rendering
export async function getStaticPaths() {
  return posts.map(post => ({
    params: { slug: post.slug }
  }));
}
---

<BaseLayout title={`${post?.title} — FunGab Global`} description={post?.content?.substring(0, 150) || ""}>
  {post ? (
    <>
      <!-- Hero Section -->
      <section class="relative min-h-[50vh] w-full text-white pt-32 pb-16 overflow-hidden">
        <img 
          src={post.image}
          alt={post.title}
          class="absolute inset-0 w-full h-full object-cover"
          loading="eager"
          decoding="sync"
        />
        <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-gradient-to-r from-black/80 via-black/70 to-black/50"></div>
        
        <div class="relative z-10 max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-16">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-4">
            <span class="inline-block px-3 py-1 text-xs font-semibold bg-[#D234C7]/20 text-[#D234C7] rounded-full">
              {post.category}
            </span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-300">{post.date}</span>
          </div>
          <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold mb-4">{post.title}</h1>
          <div class="flex items-center gap-4 text-gray-300">
            <span>By {post.author}</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Article Content -->
      <section class="py-16 px-6 md:px-16 bg-white">
        <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto prose prose-lg prose-headings:text-gray-900 prose-headings:font-bold prose-p:text-gray-700">
          <div set:html={post.content} />
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Related Posts CTA -->
      <section class="py-16 px-6 md:px-16 bg-gray-50">
        <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto text-center">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-4 text-gray-900">Explore More</h2>
          <p class="text-gray-600 mb-8">Discover more insights and tips from our blog.</p>
          <a 
            href="/blog"
            class="inline-block px-8 py-3 rounded-full bg-gradient-to-r from-[#D234C7] to-[#32BEF1] text-white font-semibold hover:opacity-90 transition-all"
          >
            Back to Blog
          </a>
        </div>
      </section>
    </>
  ) : (
    <section class="py-20 px-6 md:px-16 bg-white">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto text-center">
        <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Post Not Found</h1>
        <p class="text-gray-600 mb-8">Sorry, we couldn't find the blog post you're looking for.</p>
        <a 
          href="/blog"
          class="inline-block px-8 py-3 rounded-full bg-gradient-to-r from-[#D234C7] to-[#32BEF1] text-white font-semibold hover:opacity-90 transition-all"
        >
          Back to Blog
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>
  )}

  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>
